```
```java
package com.example.ecommerce.api.entity;

import jakarta.persistence.*;
import lombok.AllArgsConstructor;
import lombok.Builder;
import lombok.Data;
import lombok.NoArgsConstructor;

import java.math.BigDecimal;

@Data
@Builder
@NoArgsConstructor
@AllArgsConstructor
@Entity
@Table(name = "order_item")
public class OrderItem {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    @JoinColumn(name = "order_id", nullable = false)
    private Order order;

    @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    @JoinColumn(name = "product_id", nullable = false)
    private Product product;

    private Integer quantity;

    private BigDecimal priceAtOrder; // Price of the product at the time of order
}
```

This represents the data model for an item within an order, linking to both the `Order` and `Product` entities.
The price at the time of order is stored to ensure consistency, even if the product's price changes later.

**Key features:**
*   `@Id`, `@GeneratedValue`: Primary key with auto-increment.
*   `@ManyToOne`: Defines the many-to-one relationship with `Order` and `Product`. `FetchType.LAZY` is used to avoid loading related entities unless explicitly accessed, which is good for performance.
*   `@JoinColumn`: Specifies the foreign key columns (`order_id`, `product_id`).
*   `quantity`: The number of units of the product in this order item.
*   `priceAtOrder`: The price of the product when the order was placed. This is crucial for historical accuracy, as product prices can change over time.

This entity is a core part of the e-commerce domain, enabling detailed tracking of what products were bought as part of which order, at what price.